# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: angers
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The ****Croix de Guerre* 1939–1945*** (English: War Cross 1939–1945) is a French military decoration, a version of the *Croix de Guerre* created on 26 September 1939 to honour people who fought with the Allies against the Axis forces at any time during World War II.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] After Germany invaded and overran mainland France in the Battle of France in May and June 1940, this *Croix de Guerre* was replaced by the pro-Axis Vichy French government with another *Croix* with a black-and-green ribbon, while the original was upheld by Free France.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] Since the triumph of the Free French side in World War II, this version is the only one officially recognized by the French government.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The *Croix de Guerre* was designed by the sculptor Paul-Albert Bartholomé.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The medal is 37 millimetres (1.5 in) in size and is in the shape of a Maltese cross with two swords criss-crossed through the center.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] In the center of the front is the profile of the French Republic crested by a Phrygian cap.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] Around this portrait, are the words *République française* ("French Republic").
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] On the reverse of the medal are the dates of the conflict : 1939–1940, 1939–1945, or simply 1940.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The suspension and service ribbon of the medal has a red background crossed with four green lines in its center.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] On every medal and ribbon, there is at least one ribbon device, either in the shape of a palm or of a star, and fashioned from either bronze, silver, or silver-gilt (vermeil).
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The relative importance of the six possible combinations is detailed below.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The total number of devices on a *"Croix de Guerre"* is not limited.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The clasps are awarded for gallantry to any member of the French military or its allies and are, depending on the degree, roughly the equivalent to the U.S.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] Bronze Star and Silver Star or UK Military Cross and Military Medal.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The awarding of the Military Cross is carried out in a solemn ceremony with the presentation of the award.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] For example, the Soviet personnel of the Normandie-Niemen air regiment received their second Military Crosses 1939 (and Major S.D.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] Agavelyan received his third Military Cross 1939) in addition to the ones they had previously received in the USSR, personally from Charles de Gaulle.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] These *croix* were both disavowed by the Free French government and the postwar French government, and wearing them is illegal in France.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The Vichy *Croix de Guerre* employed the same tiered citations for the award as the officially-recognised version, excluding the added gilt palm.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] The Vichy War Cross 1939-1940 (Croix de guerre 1939–1940) was not prohibited as such, but it was suspended, and awards that did not fall under the provisions of Article 3 of the Decree of January 7, 1944, had to be reviewed separately.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] Those who received the "Vichy" Croix de guerre 1939-1940 for the campaigns in France and Norway in 1939-1940 (i.e., the first review of awards in 1940) automatically received the right to wear the Croix de guerre 1939 on a red-and-green ribbon.
[src:angers/1939-1945-war-cross-france] However, according to specialized foreign phaleristics sources, no review of the awards has been carried out, and there is currently no information about such a review or its results, as well as no regulations on the procedure for replacing the ribbon or the cross itself.
[src:angers/a11-autoroute] The **A 11 autoroute** is a motorway which connects Paris with Nantes via Le Mans and Angers.
[src:angers/a11-autoroute] The road is 323 kilometres (201 mi) long.
[src:angers/a11-autoroute] The following list indexes the sites worth visiting within 14 km of the road.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The abbey's origins date back to a funerary basilica (*memoria*) built to house the tomb of Bishop Albinus (529–550).
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Albinus had been buried in a cellula angusta pending completion of the great basilica, which took place between 550 and 576.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The nova basilica was soon named after Saint Aubin, as Gregory of Tours mentions ("*Dix Livres d'histoire**", l.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The funerary basilica became a monastery around the 6th–7th centuries.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] In 616, Bishop Bertrand du Mans implied monastic activity: "*venerabile Bobeno abbate de basilica sancti Albini*", as did the author of the first *Vita S.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Magnobodi* (9th or 10th century): "*abbas vocabulo Niulphus qui coenobium*".
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] A canonical community took the place of the monks in the 8th or 9th century.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Bishop Théodulf d'Orléans, accused of supporting Bernard of Italy, was detained here from 818 until his death in 820.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Saint-Aubin definitively regained its abbey status with the return of the monks in 966 (Cartulaire de Saint-Aubin, no.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] 18), when the establishment was reformed.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The monks were dispersed by the French Revolution.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The abbey church was demolished in 1811 to create what is now Place Michel-Debré, and the cloister was incorporated into the new Maine-et-Loire prefecture building.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The fortified bell tower, separate from the abbey and formerly the abbot's own property, has been preserved (the "Tour Saint-Aubin", still visible on rue des Lices).
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The bell tower of Saint-Aubin Abbey is not as old as the adjoining abbey.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] It rises 54 meters above the city of Angers.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] In the Middle Ages, the Saint-Aubin tower served as a watchtower.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] It formed a small fortress with loopholes and a well.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Like other abbey towers of the same period, it was built outside the abbey itself.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] With the ravages of time, successive occupations and multiple uses, the tower eventually fell into disrepair.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] During the 19th century, the belfry, campanile and roof were destroyed.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] It later became a shot tower for the manufacture of hunting shot.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] In 1862, the Saint-Aubin tower was listed as a *Monument Historique*.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Further protection through classification or inscription (classifications in 1901, 1904, 1968; inscription in 2007) completed this initial classification.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] In the first half of the 20th century, it housed the Musée de l'Industrie, then a meteorological observatory.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Today, it hosts temporary art exhibitions.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The abbey's Romanesque cloister stood on the site of today's Maine-et-Loire prefecture.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] It was built on the initiative of Robert de La Tour-Landry, abbot of Saint-Aubin from 1127 to 1154.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] All that remains is the eastern gallery with the Chapter house door and two series of arcades on either side.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] On the north side, they consist of two triplets of three arcades each.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] On the south side, they are composed of geminated bays beneath three framing arcades.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] These twelve arcades must have been built in the 12th century.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The doorway to the chapter house features three archivolt scrolls.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The capitals on the cloister side depict episodes from the story of Samson.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] Under the archivolts of the southern arcades, the spandrels depict scenes depicting the Maestà and the story of David and Goliath.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The monks wanted to cover the cloister with a Gothic vault in the 14th century, but this work damaged the Romanesque sculptures.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The abbey buildings were rebuilt between 1668 and 1692.
[src:angers/abbey-of-saint-aubin] The surviving cloister arcades in the courtyard of the Angers prefecture and in a room on the first floor of the prefecture's central building were classified as Historic Monuments by decree on 19 July 1901.
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] Elevation or altitude is generally expressed as "metres above mean sea level" in the metric system, or "feet above mean sea level" in United States customary and imperial units.
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] For elevations or altitudes, often just the abbreviation MSL is used, e.g., Mount Everest (8849 m MSL), or the reference to sea level is omitted completely, e.g., Mount Everest (8849 m).
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] Altimetry is the measurement of altitude or elevation above sea level.
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] Accurate measurement of historical mean sea levels is complex.
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] Land mass subsidence (as occurs naturally in some regions) can give the appearance of rising sea levels.
[src:angers/above-mean-sea-level] Conversely, markings on land masses that are uplifted (due to geological processes) can suggest a relative lowering of mean sea level.
[src:angers/acrostic] An **acrostic** is a poem or other word composition in which the *first* letter (or syllable, or word) of each new line (or paragraph, or other recurring feature in the text) spells out a word, message or the alphabet.
[src:angers/acrostic] The term comes from the French *acrostiche* from post-classical Latin *acrostichis*, from Koine Greek ἀκροστιχίς, from Ancient Greek ἄκρος "highest, topmost" and στίχος "verse".
[src:angers/acrostic] As a form of constrained writing, an acrostic can be used as a mnemonic device to aid memory retrieval.
[src:angers/acrostic] When the *last* letter of each new line (or other recurring feature) forms a word it is called a **telestich** (or **telestic**); the combination of an acrostic and a telestich in the same composition is called a **double acrostic** (e.g. the first-century Latin Sator Square).
[src:angers/acrostic] Acrostics are common in medieval literature, where they usually serve to highlight the name of the poet or his patron, or to make a prayer to a saint.
[src:angers/acrostic] They are most frequent in verse works but can also appear in prose.
[src:angers/acrostic] The Middle High German poet Rudolf von Ems for example opens all his great works with an acrostic of his name, and his world chronicle marks the beginning of each age with an acrostic of the key figure (Moses, David, etc.).
[src:angers/acrostic] In chronicles, acrostics are common in German and English but rare in other languages.
[src:angers/acrostic] Relatively simple acrostics may merely spell out the letters of the alphabet in order; such an acrostic may be called an 'alphabetical acrostic' or abecedarius.
[src:angers/acrostic] These acrostics occur in the Hebrew Bible in the first four of the five chapters of the Book of Lamentations, in the praise of the good wife in Proverbs 31:10-31, and in Psalms 9-10, 25, 34, 37, 111, 112, 119 and 145.
[src:angers/acrostic] Some acrostic psalms are technically imperfect.
[src:angers/acrostic] For example, Psalm 9 and Psalm 10 appear to constitute a single acrostic psalm together, but the length assigned to each letter is unequal and five of the 22 letters of the Hebrew alphabet are not represented and the sequence of two letters is reversed.
[src:angers/acrostic] In Psalm 25 one Hebrew letter is not represented, the following letter (*Resh*) repeated.
[src:angers/acrostic] In Psalm 34 the current final verse, 23, does fit verse 22 in content, but adds an additional line to the poem.
[src:angers/acrostic] In Psalms 37 and 111 the numbering of verses and the division into lines are interfering with each other; as a result in Psalm 37, for the letters *Daleth* and *Kaph* there is only one verse, and the letter *Ayin* is not represented.
[src:angers/acrostic] Psalm 111 and 112 have 22 lines, but 10 verses.
[src:angers/acrostic] Psalm 145 does not represent the letter *Nun*, having 21 one verses, but one Qumran manuscript of this Psalm does have that missing line, which agrees with the Septuagint.
[src:angers/acrostic] Some, like O Palmer Robertson, see the acrostic Psalms of book 1 and book 5 of Psalms as teaching and memory devices as well as transitions between subjects in the structure of the Psalms.
[src:angers/acrostic] Often the ease of detectability of an acrostic can depend on the intention of its creator.
[src:angers/acrostic] In some cases an author may desire an acrostic to have a better chance of being perceived by an observant reader, such as the acrostic contained in the *Hypnerotomachia Poliphili* (where the key capital letters are decorated with ornate embellishments).
[src:angers/acrostic] However, acrostics may also be used as a form of steganography, where the author seeks to conceal the message rather than proclaim it.
[src:angers/acrostic] This might be achieved by making the key letters uniform in appearance with the surrounding text, or by aligning the words in such a way that the relationship between the key letters is less obvious.
[src:angers/acrostic] These are referred to as *null ciphers* in steganography, using the first letter of each word to form a hidden message in an otherwise innocuous text.
[src:angers/acrostic] According to Cicero, acrostics were a regular feature of Sibylline prophecies (which were written in Greek hexameters.
[src:angers/acrostic] The type of acrostic is that known as a “gamma acrostic” (from the shape of the Greek letter Γ), where the same words are found both horizontally and vertically.
[src:angers/acrostic] Cicero refers to an acrostic in this passage using the Greek word ἀκροστιχίς.
[src:angers/acrostic] The 3rd-century BC didactic poet Aratus, who was much admired and imitated by Cicero, Virgil and other Latin writers, appears to have started a fashion for using acrostics.
[src:angers/acrostic] either it is blurred by a southerly or because rain is in the offing.” (trans.
[src:angers/acrostic] Several acrostics have recently been discovered in Roman poets, especially in Virgil.
[src:angers/acrostic] Among others, in *Eclogue* 9 the acrostic *VNDIS* 'in the waves' (lines 34–38) immediately precedes the words *quis est nam ludus in undis?* 'for what is your game in the waves?'', and *DEA DIO* (i.e.
[src:angers/acrostic] *dea Dione* 'the goddess Dione') (lines 46–51) in a passage which mentions the goddess Dione (another name for Venus).
[src:angers/acrostic] In *Eclogue* 8, alongside a passage dedicating the poem to an unnamed person and asking him to accept it, Neil Adkin reads the words *TV SI ES ACI* (i.e.
[src:angers/acrostic] *accipe*) ('if you are the one, accept!').
[src:angers/acrostic] In *Georgics* 1 429–433, next to a passage which contains the words *namque is certissimus auctor* 'for he is the most certain author', the double-letter reverse acrostic *MA VE PV* (i.e.
[src:angers/acrostic] Publius Vergilius Maro) is found on alternate lines.
[src:angers/acrostic] In Eclogue 6, 13–24 Virgil uses a double acrostic, with the same word *LAESIS* 'for those who have been harmed' going both upwards and downwards starting from the same letter L in line 19.
[src:angers/acrostic] Another double acrostic is found in *Aeneid 2*, where the word *PITHI* (i.e. πείθει, Greek for he ‘persuades’ or ‘he deceives’) is found first backwards at 103–107, then forwards at 142–146, at the beginning and end of a speech by Sinon persuading the Trojans to bring the wooden horse into the city.
[src:angers/acrostic] The discoverer of this acrostic, Neil Adkin, points out that the same word πείθει occurs at more or less exactly the same line-numbers in a repeated line describing how Odysseus’ wife Penelope deceived the suitors in *Odyssey* 2.106 and 24.141.
[src:angers/acrostic] Another transliterated Greek word used as an acrostic in a pseudo-Sibylline prophecy has recently been noticed in the syllables *DE CA TE* (i.e.
[src:angers/acrostic] Greek δεκάτη 'tenth') in Eclogue 4, 9–11, with the same *DEC A TE* repeated cryptically both forwards and backwards in line 11.
[src:angers/acrostic] In another pseudo-Sibylline prophecy in poem 5 of Tibullus book 2 the words *AVDI ME* ‘hear me!’ are picked out in the first letters of alternate lines at the beginning of the prophecy.
[src:angers/acrostic] Virgil’s friend Horace also made occasional use of acrostics, but apparently much less than Virgil.
[src:angers/acrostic] Examples are *DISCE* ‘learn!’ (*Odes* 1.18.11–15) (forming a gamma acrostic with the word *discernunt* 'they discern' in line 18) and *OTIA* 'leisure' in *Satires* 1.2.7–10, which appears just after Horace has been advised to take a rest from writing satire.
[src:angers/acrostic] The acrostic *OTIA* also occurs in Ovid, *Metamorphoses* 15.478–81, a passage describing the return of the peace-loving king Numa Pompilius to Rome.
[src:angers/acrostic] *Odes* 4.2, which starts with the word *Pindarum* '(the poet) Pindar' has next to it the truncated acrostic PIN in a gamma formation.
[src:angers/acrostic] In the first poem of Horace's *Epodes* (which were also known as *Iambi* 'iambics'), the first two lines begin *ibis ... amice*, and it has been suggested that these words were deliberately chosen so that their initial letters IBI ...
[src:angers/acrostic] In his famous lines in the *Ars Poetica*, lines 136–9, containing the proverb "mountains will give birth, but there will be born (nothing but) a ridiculous mouse", Horace writes a telestic MVS joined to the word *mus* 'mouse', adding to the humour of the passage.
[src:angers/acrostic] Towards the end of the 2nd century AD a verse-summary of the plot was added to each of the plays of Plautus.
[src:angers/acrostic] enem adiuvat sors: verum decipitur dolis.
[src:angers/acrostic] equam, qui dominum mulcat atque vilicum.
[src:angers/acrostic] The old man commissions one of them, his son the other.
[src:angers/acrostic] A lottery helps the old man; but he is deceived by tricks.
[src:angers/acrostic] a naughty one, who beats up the master and the farm-manager.
[src:angers/acrostic] The 3rd century AD poet Commodian wrote a series of 80 short poems on Christian themes called *Instructiones*.
[src:angers/acrostic] Each of these is fully acrostic (with the exception of poem 60, where the initial letters are in alphabetical order), starting with *PRAEFATIO* ‘preface’ and *INDIGNATIO DEI* ‘the wrath of God’.
[src:angers/acrostic] The initials of poem 80, read backwards, give *COMMODIANUS MENDICUS CHRISTI* ‘Commodian, Christ’s beggar’.
[src:angers/acrostic] Chapters 2–5 of Book 12 in the *Right Ginza*, a Mandaic text, are acrostic hymns, with each stanza ordered according to a letter of the Mandaic alphabet.
[src:angers/acrostic] There is an acrostic secreted in the Dutch national anthem *Wilhelmus* (*William*): the first letters of its fifteen stanzas spell WILLEM VAN NASSOV (the then name for Nassau).
[src:angers/acrostic] This was one of the hereditary titles of William the Silent, who introduces himself in the poem to the Dutch people.
[src:angers/acrostic] This title also returned in the 2010 speech from the throne, during the Dutch State Opening of Parliament, whose first 15 lines also formed WILLEM VAN NASSOV.
[src:angers/acrostic] Vladimir Nabokov's short story "The Vane Sisters" is known for its acrostic final paragraph, which contains a message from beyond the grave.
[src:angers/acrostic] An even more complicated acrostic was his sonnet "An Enigma" (1848) containing the hidden name of Sarah Anna Lewis (first letter of the first line, second letter of the second line, etc.).
[src:angers/acrostic] In 1939, Rolfe Humphries received a lifelong ban from contributing to *Poetry* magazine after he penned and attempted to publish "a poem containing a concealed scurrilous phrase aimed at a well-known person", namely Nicholas Murray Butler.
[src:angers/acrostic] Schwartz, the CEO of Sun Microsystems, sent an email to Sun employees on the completion of the acquisition of Sun by Oracle Corporation.
[src:angers/acrostic] The initial letters of the first seven paragraphs spelled "Beat IBM".
[src:angers/acrostic] James May, who would later become a presenter on the BBC program *Top Gear*, was fired from the publication *Autocar* for spelling out a message using the large red initial at the beginning of each review in the publication's *Road Test Yearbook Issue* for 1992.
[src:angers/acrostic] Properly punctuated, the message reads: "So you think it's really good, yeah?
[src:angers/acrostic] In the 2012 third novel of his *Caged Flower* series, author Cullman Wallace used acrostics as a plot device.
[src:angers/acrostic] The parents of a protagonist send e-mails where the first letters of the lines reveal their situation in a concealed message.
[src:angers/acrostic] On 19 August 2017, the members of president Donald Trump's Committee on Arts and Humanities resigned in protest over his response to the Unite the Right rally incident in Charlottesville, Virginia.
[src:angers/acrostic] The members' letter of resignation contained the acrostic "RESIST" formed from the first letter of each paragraph.
[src:angers/acrostic] On 23 August 2017, University of California, Berkeley energy professor Daniel Kammen resigned from his position as a State Department science envoy with a resignation letter in which the word "IMPEACH" was spelled out by the first letters of each paragraph.
[src:angers/acrostic] In the video game *Zork* the first letters of sentences in a prayer spelled "Odysseus" which was a possible solution to a Cyclops encounter in another room.
[src:angers/acrostic] All three seasons of the American animated series *The Owl House* use acrostics in their episode titles.
[src:angers/acrostic] After the San Jose Sharks defeated the Vegas Golden Knights in an April 24, 2022 game, the following Tuesday night during a Sharks home game saw messages on the jumbotron being shared by the team during the intermissions.
[src:angers/acrostic] One of them was a message mentioning the recent win which containing an acrostic that spelled out "Fuck the Knights".
[src:angers/acrostic] In 2023, pop singer Shakira released the song "Acróstico", which spells out the names of her children Milan and Sasha in the first letters of each line.
[src:angers/acrostic] On 4 May 2024, Noelia Voigt resigned as Miss USA 2023 with a resignation letter containing an acrostic spelling out "I am silenced".
[src:angers/acrostic] The first letters make up the acrostic and the last letters the telestich; in this case they are identical.
[src:angers/acrostic] Another example of a double acrostic is the first-century Latin Sator Square.
[src:angers/acrostic] As well as being a double acrostic, the square contains several palindromes, and it can be read as a 25-letter palindromic sentence (of an obscure meaning).
[src:angers/acrostic] The poem *Behold, O God!*, by William Browne, can be considered a complex kind of acrostic.
[src:angers/acrostic] The "INRI" at the top of the middle cross stands for *Iēsus Nazarēnus**,* *Rēx Iūdaeōrum*, Latin for "Jesus of Nazareth, King of the Jews" (John 19:19).
[src:angers/acrostic] The three quotes represent the three figures crucified on Golgotha, as recorded in the gospels of Matthew and Luke.
[src:angers/acrostic] (The text of the document shown differs significantly from the text usually published, including in the reference.
[src:angers/acrostic] The manuscript text is printed below, first as normal poetry, then spaced and bolded to bring out the acrostics.
[src:angers/acrostic] I come not, Lord, with any other merit Than what I by my Saviour Christ inherit: Be then his wounds my balm— his stripes my Bliss; His thorns my crown; my death be blest in his.
[src:angers/acrostic] And thou, my blest Redeemer, Saviour, God, Quit my accounts, withhold thy vengeful rod!
[src:angers/acrostic] O beg for me, my hopes on Thee are set; And Christ forgive me, since thou'st paid my debt The living font, the Life, the Way, I know, And but to thee, O whither shall I go?
[src:angers/acrostic] All other helps are vain: grant thine to me, For in thy cross my saving health I see.
[src:angers/acrostic] O hearken then, that I with faith implore, Lest Sin and Death sink me to rise no more.
[src:angers/acrostic] Lastly, O God, my course direct and guide, In Death defend me, that I never slide; And at Doomsday let me be rais'd again, To live with thee sweet Jesus say, Amen.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Castillon was born in Angers, in Pays de la Loire, on 24 October 2001.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] As a child, Castillon started making YouTube videos and had theatre training, though she did not consider that these two correlated with each other and did not intend to use YouTube for her career prospects.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] For the *Dissemblances* media, she made her first interview of the French actress Léa Seydoux.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] At the age of 15, with some friends, she interviewed the Dalai Lama in Dharamshala, India.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In 2017, she played Violette Hazan in the movie *Sous le même toit* directed by Dominique Farrugia.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In 2018, she played Clara in School's Out directed by Sébastien Marnier.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In 2018, Castillon met Matthieu Reynaud and formed Videoclub, over their shared love of 80s nostalgia.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Their channel had amassed over 20,000 subscribers before posting anything, to the suspicion of YouTube.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Due to Castillon's popularity on the site, their music quickly went viral there, as well as on TikTok and Spotify.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In 2019, in Milan, Adèle Castillon laid all her cards on the table to sing *Amour plastique*.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] These framed the Three of Swords tarot card, which depicts three swords piercing a heart symbolizing the experience of heartbreak.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Back in Nantes, Castillon approached film director Sirine Mamoun to film her at the location where *Amour plastique* was shot by director Julie Reynaud.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 31 March 2021, the group was dissolved when Castillon and Reynaud ended their relationship.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In May 2021, before the release of their album *Euphories*, Videoclub announced the disbandment of the group and that they would each be pursuing solo projects.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 10 June 2022, after splitting from Videoclub, she released her first song "Impala".
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 7 April 2023, she released her second single called "Rêve" (Dream).
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] At the Bois de Vincennes in Paris for the *We Love Green* festival, she wore a heart-shaped balaclava.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 16 June 2023, she released the single "Alabama", her third single as an independent artist.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 20 October 2023, Castillon launched her first album *PRD*: *Pleasure Risk Dependency*.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 31 May 2024, Castillon released "Ce Soir", which features rapper Gazo.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 24 July 2024, in Seine-Saint-Denis, Adèle Castillon served as a torchbearer, relaying the flame for the 2024 Summer Olympics.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On the eve of the opening ceremony, she and Gazo invited the audience at Parc Georges Valbon to a free concert in La Courneuve.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In 2025, Castillon released her second album *Crèvecoeur* (Heartbreaking).
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] She is currently signed to Columbia Records.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In the summer of 2025, on the Grall stage, Adèle Castillon delivered her first performance at the biggest French festival: the Vieilles Charrues.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] In Arthur Rimbaud's Charleville-Mézières, Adèle Castillon opened the Cabaret Vert Festival.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] She invited Camille Yembe to be the opening act for her concerts.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On 29 January 2025, her name was written in giant red letters on Boulevard des Capucines in Paris for her sold-out debut performance at the Olympia Hall.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Castillon's musical style draws inspiration from that of Billie Eilish.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Foreword: *Notice* from the album *PRD* is a piece composed by Benoît Heitz also known as Surkin.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] It is not a song but a recording of voices.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] The introduction of each concert features a phone call from Castillon's father, Benoît Castillon Du Perron talking to his daughter in this note.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] He wrote a book over the course of ten years, titled *Mourir avec la rivière* (English: 'Dying with the River').
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Castillon disclosed in Paulette Grisoni's podcast "The Lesson" that the couple had already separated prior to the breakup of the group Videoclub.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] She also described a difficult split, including her estrangement from the family of her ex-boyfriend and former partner, Matthieu Reynaud.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Castillon shared the reason for the breakup on TikTok but deleted the videos a few days later.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] On her arm, there is a tattoo in shape of dinosaur with the caption: 'J'ai vraiment la grosse tête' (I really have an egghead like Humpty Dumpty).
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] She hates spiders: it is not directly her but Adèle Crève-cœur who is featured in the eponymous animated music video directed by Josselin Facon.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] Either she grew up too fast, like the Disaster Girl ("Alice in the Land of Promises"), or she survived multiple medication overdoses, the "night, very late," in slow motion, bathed in the hypnotic bluish glow of her computer before heading to school.
[src:angers/adèle-castillon] She rediscovers the desire to create the *PRD* triptych: *Pleasure Risk Dependency*.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] This story is narrated in a letter from Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren, the main character and a retired Classics professor, to her daughter who has previously left South Africa and migrated to the United States to make a clear stand against apartheid.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren lives in Cape Town during the Apartheid regime.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She's just been told by her doctors that her cancer is incurable and that she's going to die soon.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Returning home, she discovers a homeless man, Vercueil, is camped out near her house.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She tells him to leave, but after he comes back again, Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren gives him food and offers him work, which seems to offend him.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Later that evening, she spots the man staring at the TV through her window.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] In the night, however, she has a sudden painful attack, and the man helps her.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] They form a sort of weird friendship as Vercueil spends most of his time near her house.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] One day she asks him to mail a letter to her daughter.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] He takes a long time to agree, but eventually he mails the letter.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren's housekeeper, Florence, returns from a trip and brings her two daughters and her son Bheki with her.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren resents having Bheki in the house, but he has no other place to go.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren thinks is a hoodlum, gets into a fight with Vercueil, who disappears for a bit.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Around this time, policemen start hanging out near the house, apparently keeping tabs on Bheki and his friends.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] When Vercueil returns, he brings home a woman and they both pass out drunk in the living room.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren starts to feel that everyone is conspiring against her to take over her property before she even dies.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren witnesses the same cops who previously talked to her disrespectfully, force Bheki and his friend, John, who are on bikes, to run into a truck.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] John injures his head badly, and she sits in the street holding his head until the ambulance arrives.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Previously insulated from racial hatred, Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Cullen starts to realize that her neat little white world doesn't match the reality of police brutality against black people.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She wants to demand justice from the authorities for John's injury, but Florence won't let her because she's afraid to be involved with the police.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] They all go to the hospital to visit Bheki's friend, but Vercueil and Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren wait in the car because she's in too much pain.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Brought to tears, she admits to him that she hasn't told her daughter about her impending death.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] He encourages her to tell the truth, so her daughter doesn't resent her after she's gone.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren invites Vercueil to sleep on the couch.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She catches herself wishing he lives there.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Tragedy strikes again when Florence gets a phone call in the middle of the night saying her son is in trouble.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren drives Florence and her daughter to Gugulethu, an unsafe place, where they meet Mr.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] They drive to a part of town in chaos - fire, screaming people, and dead bodies.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Faced with so much destruction and fear, Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren essentially throws a fit and is put to shame about her privileged sensibility by Mr.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Thabane who lectures her about the true meaning of comradeship.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] He and four other black men have been murdered and left lying against a wall, their eyes and mouths full of sand.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren finds a policeman and demands he do something, but he brushes her off.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] The next day, some women come by to pick up Florence's things, as she won't return.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren if she intends to kill herself that day.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She's unable to go through with it however, so Vercueil buys some liquor and tells her to get drunk.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Offended, she screams at him to leave, which he does.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren wakes up to find John asking about Bheki.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She tells him that his friend is dead, but the boy doesn't seem to understand.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] He's injured, so she looks after him for a bit.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] When she finds him stashing something in the floorboards one day, she calls Mr.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] The next morning the police come to her house asking about John.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She says that everything is fine, but John is afraid.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Promising not to let anything hurt him, she tries to comfort him.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] In a cruel trick, an officer distracts Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] The cops then say she can return to her home, but she can't stand the thought of it.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] She wanders the streets until she falls asleep under a bridge.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Waking to kids groping her, she's robbed and in excruciating pain.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Somehow Vercueil finds her, but she still refuses to go home.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] They fall asleep in the woods together before returning the next day.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Her house has been trashed, and a policeman is there who interrogates her about John and Vercueil.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren fades quickly as the cancer progresses.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Her pain gets worse, and she has bizarre nightmares.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Vercueil, who is caring for her now, repeatedly encourages her to commit suicide.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] They start sharing a bed so that she can stay warm.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Their relationship is completely platonic; she just can't stay warm any more.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] When she wakes up extremely cold one day, she asks Vercueil if today is the day.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Without a word, he climbs into bed and embraces her.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Her final words are that he can't make her any warmer.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren is the first-person narrator in an epistolary style.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Since she addresses her daughter in her letters as "you" the reader feels directly addressed.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Coetzee's novel can be interpreted as a coming-of-age novel since it is about Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren's perspective on the world and coming to terms with that.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Therefore, coming-of-age is in this case not growing older but rather about development.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] The title is not about the Iron Age but iron represents the rough and brutal way of life Mrs.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren and the people in Cape Town live in.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Curren does indeed think that the brutality is not something a handful of people partakes in but is a very big part in the nature of the people in Cape Town.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] However, she does underline that just like every other era in history, this time of brutality and racism will eventually come to an end.
[src:angers/age-of-iron] Coetzee brings together important themes in this book: aging, death, the confessor as hero, narrative representation, the meaning of freedom, the unity of man, familial relationships and the position of the white liberal in Apartheid South Africa.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers proper covers 42.70 square kilometres (16.49 sq mi) and has a population of 157,555 inhabitants, while around 443,900 live in its metropolitan area (*aire d'attraction*).
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Angers Loire Métropole is made up of 29 communes covering 667 square kilometres (258 sq mi) with 308,800 inhabitants (2022).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Not including the broader metropolitan area, Angers is the third most populous commune in northwestern France after Nantes and Rennes and the 18th most populous commune in France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] For centuries, Angers was an important stronghold in northwestern France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It was the cradle of the Plantagenet dynasty and became one of the intellectual centers of Europe during the reign of René of Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers developed at the confluence of three rivers, the Mayenne, the Sarthe, and the Loir, all coming from the north and flowing south towards the Loire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Their confluence, just north of Angers, creates the Maine, a short but wide river that flows into the Loire several kilometres south.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Today, Angers stands out for its specialization in the plant sector: Végépolys is Europe's leading horticultural competitiveness cluster, and the city is also home to the headquarters of the Community Plant Variety Office.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In addition, the Angers metropolitan area is a major economic centre in western France, particularly active in industry and tourism.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers enjoys a rich cultural life, made possible by its universities and museums.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The old medieval center is still dominated by the massive château of the Plantagenêts, home of the *Apocalypse Tapestry*, the biggest medieval tapestry ensemble in the world.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is also both at the edge of the Val de Loire, a World Heritage Site, and the Loire-Anjou-Touraine regional natural park.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city is first mentioned by Ptolemy around AD 150 in his *Geography*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It was then known as **Juliomagus** (Ancient Greek: Ἰουλιόμαγος, *Iouliómagos*), a name by which it also appears in the *Tabula Peutingeriana*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The name is a compound of the Latin name Julius (probably in reference to Julius Caesar) and the Celtic *magos*, "market".
[src:angers/angers-p01] Similar town dedications were common in Roman Gaul, and toponyms often kept a Gallic element.
[src:angers/angers-p01] When the location needed to be distinguished from other Juliomagi, it was known as **Juliomagus Andecavorum** ("Juliomagus of the Andecavi"), in reference to the principal Gallic tribe in and around the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Around AD 400, the city came to be referred to as the **civitas Andecavorum** ("tribal capital of the Andecavi").
[src:angers/angers-p01] This was a common change in Gaul, also seen in the names of Paris, Tours and Évreux around this time.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the Middle Ages, the late Latin name gradually developed into the modern one.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The form **Angiers** appeared during the 12th century and was later corrupted to "Angers".
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Latin *Andecavum* also gave Anjou its name.
[src:angers/angers-p01] This double formation is also quite common in France and can be seen in Poitiers and Poitou, and Bourges and Berry.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers was traditionally known as the "Black City" (*la Ville Noire*) because many roofs were built of slate, due to the quarry in neighbouring Trélazé.
[src:angers/angers-p01] These have become less common since the development of the city in the 19th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The coat of arms of Angers bears the French royal fleur de lys of the dukes of Anjou (the first duke was the son of the king of France, Jean II); the key evokes the stronghold position of the city close to the Breton border.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Under Napoleon I's rule, Angers was one of the "Bonnes villes"(fr) and was therefore allowed to ask for a new coat of arms.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The bees, symbol of the First French Empire, then replaced the royal fleurs de lys.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1949, Angers received the 1939–1945 War Cross and since then, the decoration is sometimes placed between the two fleurs de lys.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is located at the geographical center of the Maine-et-Loire department, on the road (A11 autoroute, *L'Océane*) which connects Paris to the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city is situated just south of the confluence of the Loir, Mayenne and Sarthe, which form together the river Maine.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Maine crosses Angers and heads south towards the Loire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The confluence of the three rivers and the proximity of the Loire make up a natural crossroads which favoured the foundation of the antique *Juliomagus*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is located 91 km (57 mi) from Nantes, 124 km (77 mi) from Rennes, 132 km (82 mi) from Poitiers and 297 km (185 mi) from Paris.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It is also 118 km (73 mi) far from Pornic, the closest sea resort, situated on the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Elevation varies 12 to 64 meters (39 to 210 ft) above sea level.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is a hilly town, particularly marked by a rocky promontory dominating the lower valley of Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] This was the site of the ancient city and still houses the town's castle, cathedral, and medieval quarters.
[src:angers/angers-p01] At the north and south, where the river Maine arrives in and leaves Angers, the landscape is formed by islands, ponds and floodplains which are a haven for birds and a typical flora of the Val de Loire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The étang Saint-Nicolas and Lac de Maine (fr) both artificial, are among the biggest green areas of the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The commune of Angers is bordered by ten other communes which form various suburbs.
[src:angers/angers-p01] These are, clockwise, Avrillé, Cantenay-Épinard, Écouflant, Saint-Barthélemy-d'Anjou, Trélazé, Les Ponts-de-Cé, Sainte-Gemmes-sur-Loire, Bouchemaine and Beaucouzé.
[src:angers/angers-p01] 22 other communes situated farther form with them the Communauté urbaine Angers Loire Métropole.
[src:angers/angers-p01] All these peripheral communes are situated within 17 km (11 mi) from Angers proper.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Together, they have around 272,400 inhabitants.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers has an oceanic climate, with moderate rain year-round.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Winters have scarce frosts and snowfalls, and summers are warm and sunny.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The oldest streets and buildings in Angers are located on the promontory where the Angers castle stands.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The urban structure there dates back from the 13th, 14th and 15th centuries.
[src:angers/angers-p01] A military presence there was attested from the 3rd century and some remains of an antique city wall are still visible on the castle grounds.
[src:angers/angers-p01] This wall was built to protect the city from the Germanic invasions of AD 275 and 276.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the Middle Ages, the castle was the core of the city's defence system, composed of tall city walls and river chains which prevented enemy ships from going up the Maine.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The walls were last reconstructed between 1230 and 1240, by order of King Louis IX.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Today, portions of the wall are still visible in Rue Toussaint and on Boulevard Carnot, as are some towers, like the *Tour Villebon* and the *Tour des Anglais*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Before the first cadastre (1810), the city had not extended much beyond its medieval limits: on and around the castle promontory, with some dwellings on the other bank of the Maine in a neighbourhood called *La Doutre*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] That part of the city developed quickly during the industrial revolution and became a big river port.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Industry was encouraged by firms like Bessonneau (textile factories) and Cointreau (distillery).
[src:angers/angers-p01] After 1850, many suburbs appeared around the train stations and the slate quarries to the south in Trélazé.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Despite the port in La Doutre, demographic growth and urban extension were more significant on the eastern bank of the Maine, where the former Juliomagus had been founded.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The medieval city center was redeveloped and expanded from 1791.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Place du Ralliement*, the main square, was then built in place of three churches destroyed during the French Revolution and, later, ring boulevards planted with trees replaced the city walls.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The architectural style used is mainly Haussmanian, but there are also some Palladian, Art Nouveau or Art Deco buildings.
[src:angers/angers-p01] After 1945 and the Second World War, several large council estates made of tower blocks were built around the city center, the first of them being Belle-Beille in 1953.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Industrial activity changed drastically: port activity declined while new factories, such as Technicolor SA in 1957, were built.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 1970s, the collective approach to urban development gave way to more individual houses being built for the middle class.
[src:angers/angers-p01] As the metropolitan area continued to grow, commuting became more common.
[src:angers/angers-p01] New shopping areas were constructed close to the villages which had been subsumed into the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Because of the floodplains that surround the city north and south, Angers can only grow significantly on an east–west axis.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Being both at the edge of the Val de Loire World Heritage site and on the largest river confluence in France, Angers has a high natural potential, notably highlighted by the Saint-Aubin island, situated north of the center and covering a tenth of the city total surface.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Protected, the island is formed of swamps and natural meadows.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The oldest green areas date back from the Renaissance, when the moats of the castle were transformed into pleasure and kitchen gardens.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Similar gardens were built by the aristocracy around their hôtels particuliers and physic garden were planted in hospices cloisters.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Jardin des plantes, the first botanical garden, dates back from the beginning of the 18th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 19th century, others were built, for example the Faculty of Pharmacy garden and the Roseraie.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The first recreational parks, for their part, were built during the Second French Empire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The étang Saint-Nicolas, made by a sluice on a small river, the Brionneau, was protected as early as 1936.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Jardin du Mail (*Mall Garden*), an esplanade situated outside the ring boulevards, was built between 1820 and 1880 on the former Champs de Mars (Fields of Mars, a place where the garrisons used to train and parade).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Another esplanade, the Mail François Mitterrand, was built in 1999 together with a garden inside the new Saint-Serge business district.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 1960s the old gravel pits around the Maine were filled with water to form the Lac de Maine, which now hosts a marina.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 2010, a large amusement park, Terra Botanica, was inaugurated close to Saint-Aubin island.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The first sign of human presence in Angers dates back to around 400,000 BC.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Vestiges from the Neolithic are more abundant and include numerous polished stone axes.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Burials from 4500 x 3500 BC were also discovered on the castle grounds.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 5th century BC, the Andecavi, a Celtic people, settled north of the Loire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] By the end of the Iron Age, Angers was a relatively densely populated hillfort.
[src:angers/angers-p01] While the settlement's Roman name—Juliomagus—may be older, it is only attested from the 3rd century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Roman town consisted of many villas and baths and had an amphitheater as well as a Mithraeum, a temple dedicated to Mithra.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Successive Germanic invasions in AD 275 and 276 forced the inhabitants to move to the highest point of their city and to build a wall around a small area of around 9 hectares (22 acres).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers received its first bishop in 372 during the election of Martin of Tours.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The first abbey, Saint-Aubin, was built during the 7th century to house the sarcophagus of Saint Albinius.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Saint-Serge Abbey was founded by the Merovingian kings Clovis II and Theuderic III a century later.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 2008, ten Frankish sarcophagi from that period were discovered where Saint-Morille church once stood during the tramway construction.
[src:angers/angers-p01] From the 850s, Angers suffered from its situation on the border with Brittany and Normandy.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In September 851, Charles the Bald and Erispoe, a Breton chief, met in the town to sign the Treaty of Angers, which secured Breton independence and fixed the borders of Brittany.
[src:angers/angers-p01] However, the situation remained dangerous for Angers, and Charles the Bald created in 853 a wide buffer zone around Brittany comprising parts of Anjou, Touraine, Maine and Sées, which was ruled by Robert the Strong, a great-grandfather of Hugh Capet.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 870, the Viking chief Hastein seized Angers where he settled until a successful siege temporarily displaced him.
[src:angers/angers-p01] He again took control of the town in 873, before the Carolingian Emperor ousted him.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Fulk I of Anjou, a Carolingian descendant, was the first viscount of Angers (before 898 until 929) and of Tours (898–909), and count of Nantes (909–919).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Around 929, he took the title of count (earl) of Angers and founded the first Anjou dynasty, the House of Ingelger (*French: Ingelgériens*).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers subsequently formed the capital of the province of Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 12th century, after internal divisions in Brittany, the county of Nantes was annexed by Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Henry II Plantagenêt kept it for more than 30 years.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The grandson of Henry I of England, he also succeeded to the English crown and ruled the vast Angevin Empire, which stretched from the Pyrenees to Ireland.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The castle of Angers was then the seat of the Court and the dynasty.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Empire disappeared in 1204–1205 when the King of France, Philip II, seized Normandy and Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Henceforth, there were no more counts of Anjou, as the French king had made Anjou a dukedom.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Now a part of the Kingdom of France, Angers became the "Key to the Kingdom" (*Clé du Royaume*) facing still independent Brittany.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1228, during Louis IX's minority, Blanche of Castile decided to fortify the city and to rebuild the castle.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Later, during the 1350s and 1360s, the schools of Law, Medicine and Theology, renowned in Europe, were organized into a university.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1373, Louis I of Naples and Anjou ordered the six tapestries illustrating the Apocalypse of St John known today as the *Apocalypse Tapestry*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] King René of Anjou contributed to the economic revival in a city that had been diminished by the Black Death (1347–1350) and the Hundred Years War (1337–1453).
[src:angers/angers-p01] A man of great culture and generosity, René transformed Angers into a cultural and political center and held court there.
[src:angers/angers-p01] He transformed the castle moat into a menagerie and built several gardens.
[src:angers/angers-p01] He also founded in Angers a new Ordre du Croissant which was supposed to compete with the Order of the Golden Fleece, created several years earlier.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1474, Louis XI, in his attempt to conquer Anjou, came to Angers with his army, asking for the keys of the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] René, then 65 years old, did not want to lead a war against his nephew and surrendered his domains without a fight.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Thus, Anjou ceased to be an appanage and fell into the Royal domain.
[src:angers/angers-p01] After his death, René was buried in 1480 in Saint-Maurice cathedral.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1551, Angers became the seat of a bailiwick and the presidial court of a jurisdiction, a position the city kept until 1790.
[src:angers/angers-p01] At the same time, with the growth of Protestantism in France, a Catholic was placed at the head of the city and its castle while the bourgeoisie formed a Catholic militia to protect Angers from the Huguenots.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The bishop, Gabriel Bouvery, organized on his side an "Angevin League".
[src:angers/angers-p01] Bartholomew's Day massacre reached Angers, another massacre took place in the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The bodies of slain Protestants were thrown into the Mayenne.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It was the aldermen who stopped the slaughter.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1598, the Edict of Nantes was prepared by Henri IV in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] From 6 March until 2 April, Angers was the *de facto* capital of France and the King tried all means to satisfy the Catholics of the city, for example by laying the cornerstone of the new Capucine convent.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1619, Louis XIII gave the governance of Anjou to his mother, Marie de' Medici.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Queen Mother settled in Angers, at the Logis Barrault, with her chaplain, Cardinal Richelieu.
[src:angers/angers-p01] At the premature death of Louis XIII in 1643, his son Louis XIV was only an infant.
[src:angers/angers-p01] France was troubled at this time by several famines and epidemics, and by political instability.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1649, the people of Angers revolted against rising taxes, the start of the Fronde in Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Fronde was a nationwide military conflict opposing some aristocrats wanting more autonomy and the Royal forces loyal to Anne of Austria as Queen Mother and Regent, and her prime minister, Cardinal Mazarin.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Royalist repression in Angers was narrowly averted by Bishop Henri Arnauld, who interceded with the Queen Mother.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Arnauld, who would remain Bishop of Angers until 1692, was to leave a deep mark on the religious life of the city during the second half of the 17th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1652, Henri Chabot, Duke of Rohan and governor of Anjou, decided to back Louis of Condé, leader of the Fronde.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers again became rebellious and Louis XIV sent his army to seize it.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Duke of Rohan immediately surrendered and thus again prevented the sack of the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The first months of the French Revolution were relatively quiet in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1789, the city lost its ancient administrative positions, replaced in 1790 by the department of *Mayenne-et-Loire*, soon renamed "Maine-et-Loire".
[src:angers/angers-p01] Anjou, as a political entity, disappeared, although the new department included most of its territory.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The War of Vendée, a Royalist rebellion and counterrevolution led in Vendée, a department located at the southwest of Maine-et-Loire, reached the Loire in March 1793.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Royalist army soon crossed the river and progressed as far as Granville, in Normandy, in November.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Pushed back, the Vendéens went back south and, to cross the Loire again, had to attack Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city was defended by 4,000 Republican soldiers, whereas the Royalists were at least 20,000, but weakened by successive fights and deceases.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Siege of Angers occurred on 3 and 4 December 1793.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Royalists' bad tactics, as well as the strength of Angers city wall and castle, caused their loss.
[src:angers/angers-p01] They consequently went back north for a while, around Le Mans, before crossing the Loire at Ancenis on 16 December.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1794, fierce repression was conducted in the whole region against the Royalists.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In Angers, 290 prisoners were shot and 1020 died of illness in jail.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city also welcomed many refugees, mostly Republicans living in Royalist rural areas.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Between 19 and 31 May 1793, between 650 and 1000 Republican families sought asylum in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 19th century, the city was deeply influenced by the urban transformations in Paris.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city traditionally had a somewhat sombre appearance from the quantity of local slate used in construction but many quarters were gradually destroyed, redeveloped, or rebuilt on the Parisian model.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city wall, which formed a square around the old city core, was demolished around 1850 and replaced by wide boulevards.
[src:angers/angers-p01] New districts of the city were also opened up on the opposite bank of the river.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Hôtel de Ville (City Hall) was officially opened as a municipal building on 23 September 1823.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1849, the Angers-Saumur railway was built; it was extended to Nantes two years later.
[src:angers/angers-p01] When completed, the line connected Paris to the Atlantic coast.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1850, a catastrophic failure of the Angers Bridge suspension bridge caused the deaths of over 200 soldiers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The disaster inhibited the construction of suspension bridges in France for two decades.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The accident was mainly caused by soldiers' lilting march which created resonance in the bridge structure.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It was soon assimilated to the medieval Angevin University (*Universitas Andegavensis*), which had been dissolved during the French Revolution.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The new faculty was canonically erected as the Catholic University of Angers (*Université catholique d'Angers*) by Pope Pius IX in 1879.
[src:angers/angers-p01] However, in 1890, a law prohibited private institutions of higher education from calling themselves "universities".
[src:angers/angers-p01] The institution was then renamed the "Free Faculty of Angers" (*Faculté libre d'Angers*), although it kept its original name on an informal basis.
[src:angers/angers-p01] At the beginning of the 20th century, two higher education establishments, specializing in agriculture and commercial sciences, were opened.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the first half of the 20th century, several Art Nouveau and Art Deco buildings were constructed, such as the *Nouvelles Galeries*, the *Hotel des Postes*, *Hotel Continental*, the *Alcazar* and the *Maison bleue*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In September 1939, when Poland was invaded by Germany, the Polish government-in-exile settled in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It left the city on 12 June 1940, after the invasion of France by the *Wehrmacht*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers fell to the Nazis during the same month.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Germans made it the seat of a regional Kommandantur.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1941, a first Resistance movement, called *Honneur et Patrie*, was created in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] 60 Resistants were shot at the Belle-Beille range in 1942 and a German bunker factory employed 6000 people in 1943.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In July 1942, 853 Jews were arrested and sent to Auschwitz.
[src:angers/angers-p01] On the night of 28 May 1944, the first Allied bombing occurred over the Saint-Laud quarter.
[src:angers/angers-p01] 243 people died and many others were wounded.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Successive attacks on 29 and 30 May destroyed the train station and its surroundings which were reconstructed in the 1950s.
[src:angers/angers-p01] After liberating Avranches and Rennes, General George Patton and his 5th infantry division arrived in Anjou on 5 August.
[src:angers/angers-p01] To seize Angers, they decided to enter the city by its eastern side to surprise the Nazis.
[src:angers/angers-p01] On 9 August, they crossed the Maine and started the fight.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Helped by the local French Forces of the Interior, they progressively moved forward to the city center.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The fight was nevertheless difficult and Angers was liberated the day after, at around 5 p.m.
[src:angers/angers-p01] After the end of the war, the city experienced quick development and demographic growth.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 1971, a decision was made to reestablish a public university, and the Université catholique d'Angers was split between the Université catholique de l'Ouest (private) and the Université d'Angers (public).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers continues to have two different universities.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Later, other urban plans were drawn up, with a new emphasis on nature and heritage protection, as well as on social mixing.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 1990s, the redevelopment of the Saint-Serge quarter, located just north of the historical center, produced a new business center, gardens and university buildings.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers received its communal charter from Louis XI in February 1475, but free elections for the mayor and aldermen were not guaranteed before 1484, following a decision by Charles VIII.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Since then, 75 successive mayors have governed Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Until the Second World War, Angers was mainly governed by centrist and republican mayors.
[src:angers/angers-p01] From 1977 until 2014, all the successive mayors were members of the Socialist Party, whereas the Maine-et-Loire department has always been governed by moderate right-wing parties.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The current mayor (as at May 2023) is Jean-Marc Verchère.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is divided into eight cantons; most of them include parts of Angers plus some surrounding communes.
[src:angers/angers-p01] These cantons are not administrative entities and only serve to elect the members of the department council.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The INSEE, the French institute for statistics, divides the commune of Angers into twelve sectors.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Depending on their social and economic issues, some of them can have priority for financial assistance and urban regeneration.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In Angers, five are considered as priority sectors, three as sensitive urban areas, and one as an urban free zone.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Being the chef-lieu of Maine-et-Loire, Angers is the seat of a prefecture.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It is also the seat of a Court of Appeal and of several regional or local institutes, concerning for example, customs, education or science.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers also has several other courts of justice as well as a prison.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is the 18th most populated commune in France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In 2022, the urban area (*unité urbaine*), which encompasses Angers plus eleven surrounding communes (243.3 square kilometers (93.9 square miles) in total), had 250,031 inhabitants.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The metropolitan area (*aire d'attraction*) included in 2022 81 communes, 443,887 inhabitants and 2,419 square kilometres (934 square miles).
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Angers Loire Métropole, an economic and political association of communes, includes 29 communes and around 309,000 inhabitants.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The population of Angers is relatively young, with 38% of the population being younger than 25 and 18% of residents over 65 years old.
[src:angers/angers-p01] This is partially explained by the presence of two universities, 21.0% of the population between 15 and 64 being pupils and students in 2017.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The early prosperity of the town was largely due to the nearby quarries of slate, whose abundant use for the roofs of Angers led to its sobriquet as the "Black City".
[src:angers/angers-p01] In the mid-19th century, the principal manufactures were goods for sailing ships (sailcloth and rope), linen and hose, sugar, leather, wax, and oil, as well as agricultural products (mainly wheat, wine, and fruit).
[src:angers/angers-p01] By the time of the First World War, Cointreau had developed the distillation of liqueurs from the area's fruit to an industrial level.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The work for sailing ships was still carried on but steamships had greatly reduced demand.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Instead, local companies produced cables, wires, and thread and increased production of footwear, umbrellas, and parasols.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The area's vineyards focused on sparkling wine and fruit was increasingly preserved for sale elsewhere.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The area had also developed a small-scale textile industry and begun producing machines, as well as commercial-scale production of hemp and flowers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Present-day Angers provides 45.7% of the Maine-et-Loire job positions.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It is the 22nd-largest national job provider and the 3rd-largest one in northwestern France after Nantes and Rennes.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Its unemployment rate (13.5% in 2017) is above the national rate.
[src:angers/angers-p01] 20.7% of the people working in Angers have graduate or post-graduate qualifications.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Cointreau continues to produce its orange triple-sec liqueur in nearby Saint-Barthélemy-d'Anjou, but many of the other industries have since vanished.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Modern Angers produces Scania trucks at Écouflant and computers by Bull, Packard Bell, and NEC.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It also supports research labs investigating horticulture and biotechnology.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Thanks to its several higher education schools, laboratories, and various offices, Angers is the largest horticultural center in Europe and, as the home of the Community Plant Variety Office, Angers is the hub of the plant breeders' rights system in the European Community.
[src:angers/angers-p01] For example, Angers is the leading hydrangeas producer in Europe.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The local economy also relies on the presence of many administrative, educational, and health institutions.
[src:angers/angers-p01] There are also many small firms, chiefly focused on the agricultural tradition of Maine-et-Loire.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers also serves as a regional financial center, with many banks and insurance companies (including Afone, CNP Assurances, Crédit Agricole, Fiducial, and Groupama) maintaining their regional offices there.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is an important convention center, with a present convention trade of around €8,000,000.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The new convention center slated for 2016 has been cancelled in 2013.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The renovation of the previous convention center and the addition of a 400 conference room at the back by the garden should be finished in 2018.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Parc des Expositions*, where fairs are currently held, welcomes 600,000 visitors and more than 300 events each year.
[src:angers/angers-p01] With its 27,000 m2 (290,626 sq ft), it is the biggest structure of its type in northwestern France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Hôtel-Dieu*, founded in the 12th century, is one of the oldest hospitals in France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] First located in the *Hospice Saint-Jean*, it moved into new buildings in 1870; it became Centre Hospitalier Universitaire (CHU) in 1966.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It has 1,500 beds and around 5,500 people work there.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Two private hospitals and a regional center for re-education also exist.
[src:angers/angers-p01] A center of learning, Angers boasts two renowned universities and several specialized institutions, altogether enrolling more than 26,000 students.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Catholic University of the West (*Université Catholique de L'Ouest* or UCO) is one of five Catholic universities in France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The town is also home to a state university, the University of Angers, best university in France in 2015 for success rates.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is also home to engineering graduate schools, such as the Arts et Métiers ParisTech, top school in mechanical and industrial engineering and the ESEO, an engineering school in electronics and computer science and ESAIP, an engineering school in risk management and environment.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Its education and research institutes are the driving force behind the city's science and technology industries.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers's other educational institutions include *lycées*, training colleges, and a school of fine art.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Another Angers's Business School is ESSCA (*École Supérieure des Sciences Commerciales d'Angers*).
[src:angers/angers-p01] Formerly part of the UCO, the school's Master's program is of a duration of five years.
[src:angers/angers-p01] ESSCA recruits students after the Baccalaureat.
[src:angers/angers-p01] In addition to French schools and universities, an American university, St.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Edward's University, has a new expanding campus in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Edward's University is a diverse, Catholic liberal arts institution from Austin, Texas.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The university has a partnership with UCO, and offers a variety of courses of undergraduate level and professional training.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is situated on the crossroads of three highways, the A11, to Paris and Nantes, the A87 to La Roche-sur-Yon and the A85 to Tours and Lyon.
[src:angers/angers-p01] National roads connect the city with Rennes, Caen and Laval.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Before the construction of bypasses during the 2000s, the A11 crossed the city center, following the river Maine, and passed just below the castle.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Causing air pollution and noise and disfiguring the Maine quays, the portions of the former highway which are still in place should be redeveloped in the coming years.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers inaugurated the new Irigo tram system on 25 June 2011.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The tramway consists of one 12 km (7.46 mi) line with 25 stops.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The line runs from Avrillé-Ardenne in the north to Angers-Roseraie in the south, passing by the center and the train station.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Service is provided by Keolis using 17 Alstom Citadis trams.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The system uses partial ground-level power supply, which avoids aerial wires and preserves the historical character of the city center.
[src:angers/angers-p01] A second line is scheduled for 2018–2022.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Besides the tram, Irigo also organizes the bus network in Angers consisting of 13 urban lines and 12 suburban lines.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The bus station, situated outside the Angers Saint-Laud train station, is a hub for the departmental bus network (*Anjoubus*) and is also served by international bus companies.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers is on both the Nantes-Paris and Nantes-Lyon railways.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city has several train stations, all originally built in the 19th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Some are still in use; others are closed or reserved for freight.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The main station, Angers Saint-Laud, is on a TGV line and has direct TGV services to Paris (1 hour 30 minutes), Lyon (3 hours 45 minutes), Strasbourg (4 hours 35 minutes), and Lille (3 hours 25 minutes), as well as Avignon, Marseille and Montpellier.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Regional trains go to Cholet, Saumur, Tours, Blois, Nevers and Bourges.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The nearest airport is Angers - Loire Airport, which replaced in 1998 an older airport near the Saint-Aubin island.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The airport is located in the commune of Marcé, 20 kilometers (12 miles) from Angers and close to the A11 and the A85.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It can receive 50,000 passengers per year.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Château d'Angers, built on a schist promontory, dominates the river Maine and the old town.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Its site has been occupied since antiquity; the castle itself was built between 1230 and 1240 by Louis IX of France.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The massive walls are about one kilometer long and punctuated by 17 towers; they were built with horizontal slices of tuff and schist, giving it strength and an original striped look.
[src:angers/angers-p01] During the 15th century, a chapel and the Châtelet were added in the courtyard.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Maison d'Adam* ("Adam's House"), located behind the cathedral, is an excellent example of the half-timbered houses which were built during the Middle Ages.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Many similar houses, although smaller, are also visible along the streets around the castle.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city also displays several Renaissance and classical hôtels particuliers, the most renowned being the *Logis Pincé* from the 16th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Maison bleue* ("Blue House"), built in 1927, is an Art Deco masterpiece.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The former seat of the French Aviation Company (*Compagnie française d'Aviation*) was built in 1938 and abandoned during the Second World War.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Totally refurbished in 2004, it is now a testimony to 1930s architecture.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Angers Cathedral is a major landmark in the cityscape, with its two spires culminating at 75 meters (246 ft).
[src:angers/angers-p01] The construction of the current building started during the 12th century on the remains of an older sanctuary.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The original structure, romanesque, received gothic columns and vaults in the middle of the 12th century, giving birth to the Angevin gothic, a style that quickly spread in Western France and the Angevin possessions in Italy.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Sculptures and architectural details were added to the façade during the 16th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The twin spires were built in 1518 and 1523.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The neighbouring *Palais du Tau*, the former episcopal palace, dates from the 12th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The skyline is also marked by the *Tour Saint-Aubin*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Completed in 1170, it was the bell-tower of an abbey closed during the French Revolution and destroyed in 1810.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Elaborately sculptured 11th and 12th century arcades also survive in the courtyard of the Prefecture.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Another abbey, the *Abbaye Toussaint*, founded during the 13th century, was also partially pulled down and only the church and parts of the cloister are still visible.
[src:angers/angers-p01] On the southern limits of the commune, close to the Maine, stands the *Couvent de la Baumette*, founded during the 15th century by René of Anjou.
[src:angers/angers-p01] La Doutre, an old quarter located on the western bank of the Maine and facing the castle, contains two major medieval sites, the former *Abbaye du Ronceray*, built during the 11th and 12th century, and the *Hôpital Saint-Jean*, founded by Henry II of England and used as the city hospital until 1870.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Musée des Beaux-Arts d'Angers, located in the Renaissance *Logis Barrault*, displays a collection of paintings and sculptures dating from the 14th century to today.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It is particularly renowned for its 18th-century paintings, including works by Jean-Baptiste Greuze, Van Loo, Antoine Watteau, Jean-Honoré Fragonard, and Jean Siméon Chardin.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The museum also contains a graphic design studio, a gallery devoted to the history of Angers and a temporary exhibition gallery.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The institution has an annexe at the château in Villevêque, a village located several kilometers north of the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Inside the castle, a special gallery displays the *Apocalypse Tapestry*, ordered by Louis I of Naples at the end of the 14th century.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It is more than 140 meters (460 ft) long, the largest medieval tapestry in the world.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Inspired by manuscript miniatures, the successive scenes, designed by Jean Bondol, illustrate the Apocalypse of St John.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Located inside the old *Hôpital Saint-Jean*, the *Musée Jean-Lurçat et de la tapisserie contemporaine* displays tapestries dating from the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The museum is dedicated to Jean Lurçat, an artist noted for his role in the revival of contemporary tapestry, and notably exhibits his "*Chant du Monde*", a modern echo to the *Apocalypse Tapestry* made after the bombing of Hiroshima.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Muséum d'histoire naturelle d'Angers has been located in the 1521 Hôtel Demarie-Valentin since 1885.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It exhibits a large collection of mounted animals and fossils, divided in three departments, one for zoology, one for botany and the last one for paleontology and geology.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Logis Pincé*, constructed during the Renaissance, is the home of the museum of the same name.
[src:angers/angers-p01] It displays Egyptian, Greek, Roman, and Etruscan antiquities as well as Chinese and Japanese artifacts.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Located in the *Abbaye Toussaint*, the *Galerie David d'Angers* gathers sculptures, reliefs, and medallions by David d'Angers, a 19th-century sculptor born in the city.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The gallery also owns the preparatory works for the Panthéon of Paris pediment.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers also enjoys a *Maison de l'Architecture*, which organizes various exhibitions and workshops, as well as several temporary exhibition galleries distributed in the city center.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Outside the commune limits are also an aviation museum and a museum of communications.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Grand Théâtre, dominating the Place du Ralliement, was first built in 1791, but destroyed by a fire in 1853.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The existing building was completed in 1871 and its auditorium contains six stalls and four balconies, totalling 730 seats.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Théâtre du Quai, inaugurated in 2007, has two auditoriums: one contains 980 seats and several balconies, and the other, more flexible, can welcome 400 seated or 960 standing spectators.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Grand Théâtre and the Théâtre du Quai are the venues of three institutions, Angers-Nantes Opéra, an opera company also based in Nantes, the Contemporary Dance National Center (CNDC), inaugurated by Alwin Nikolais in 1978, and the Nouveau théâtre d'Angers (NTA).
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Orchestre National des Pays de la Loire, shared with Nantes, usually performs at the Congress Center, built in 1983, with a capacity of 1,240 seats.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Other concert halls include the *Chabada*, the *Amphitéa* and the former Ursuline chapel.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Local theater companies perform at Théâtre Chanzy, Théâtre du Champ de Bataille, Théâtre de la Comédie or at the Centre Jean Vilar.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Each September, the city organizes a street performance festival, called the *Accroche-Cœurs*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The *Chabada*, a popular concert hall, is the cradle of the Angevin contemporary scene and several groups and performers were discovered there, Les Thugs, a punk band formed in 1983, being the first ones.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The local scene also includes the alternative rock group La Ruda, the power pop band Pony Pony Run Run, the world music band Lo'Jo and Titi Robin, a performer influenced by Gypsy and Arabic music.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The Premiers Plans festival, dedicated to European first films and meant to help new directors meet their audience, is conducted every year and lasts one week.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The films are screened in three small cinemas, while two big generalist multiplexes also exist in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Angers had a local TV channel *Angers 7* which went bankrupt in 2010 and was replaced 3 years later by *Angers Télé*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The national French channel France 3, however, still presents local news in its programs.
[src:angers/angers-p01] Several national radio stations, such as Virgin Radio, NRJ and Chérie FM maintain local antennas in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city is also the home of two local stations, *Radio Campus* and *Radio G!*.
[src:angers/angers-p01] *Ouest-France* and *Le Courrier de l'Ouest* are the two local newspapers, the last one having its headquarters in Angers.
[src:angers/angers-p01] The city and Angers Loire Métropole also edit their news bulletins.
[src:angers/angers-p02] Angers has many sport teams playing at top levels.
[src:angers/angers-p02] The club was created in 1919 and returned to Ligue 1 (French top league) in 2015 after 21 years.
[src:angers/angers-p02] Les Ducs d'Angers is Angers's ice hockey team.
[src:angers/angers-p02] The club plays in the Magnus League (first division).
[src:angers/angers-p02] Anjou BC is Angers's basketball team, playing in second division.
[src:angers/angers-p02] Vaillante Angers is Angers's table tennis team playing in top division Pro A since the 2000–2001 season.
[src:angers/angers-p02] Angers also acts as home to the Angers Aviron Nautique, a rowing club which actively competes in regattas across France.
[src:angers/angers-p02] Raymond Kopa Stadium is the main sports venue which can hold 18,000 people.
[src:angers/angers-p02] The city also has a variety of sports halls, tennis courts, swimming pools, shooting and archery stands, a velodrome, a rowing center, an ice rink and a fencing hall.
[src:angers/angers-p02] The Lac de Maine Stadium hosted the athletics championships in France in July 2009.
